00:04:05.220 --> 00:04:05.680
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah.

00:04:05.680 --> 00:04:07.800
So for those that aren't
familiar, Semester at Sea

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:09.633
is a cruise ship that
goes around the world.

00:04:09.633 --> 00:04:13.230
And you most the time stop
in anywhere from EIGHT

00:04:13.230 --> 00:04:15.089
to 13 countries--
every voyage has

00:04:15.089 --> 00:04:16.380
a slightly different itinerary.

00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:19.130
But my year it was supposed
to be 10-- different countries

00:04:19.130 --> 00:04:21.660
across Asia, Africa
and Latin America.

00:04:21.660 --> 00:04:25.810
And I'm part of one of
the three famous voyages.

00:04:25.810 --> 00:04:27.343
And you don't get
famous on Semester

00:04:27.343 --> 00:04:29.550
at Sea unless something
goes really wrong.

00:04:29.550 --> 00:04:32.740
So my ship left from
Vancouver headed

00:04:32.740 --> 00:04:35.530
toward South Korea,
January, 2005.

00:04:35.530 --> 00:04:37.114
And while crossing
the North Pacific--

00:04:37.114 --> 00:04:39.488
it was the very first time
that they had gone that route.

00:04:39.488 --> 00:04:41.170
They always went
the other direction.

00:04:41.170 --> 00:04:42.950
But they had a brand
new ship my year

00:04:42.950 --> 00:04:44.710
and they decided that
it was OK to cross

00:04:44.710 --> 00:04:46.870
the North Pacific in winter.

00:04:46.870 --> 00:04:49.376
And three major storm
fronts developed.

00:04:49.376 --> 00:04:51.125
We tried to go underneath,
and another one

00:04:51.125 --> 00:04:52.240
developed underneath us.

00:04:52.240 --> 00:04:55.530
And we got caught in
essentially a superstorm.

00:04:55.530 --> 00:04:58.210
And there's a 30 minute
"Storm Stories" episode

00:04:58.210 --> 00:05:01.600
just on my ship that's on
YouTube that can look up.

00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:04.150
But we were struck
by 60 foot rogue wave

00:05:04.150 --> 00:05:06.130
about 800 miles from land.

00:05:06.130 --> 00:05:07.630
And it went over
the top of our ship

00:05:07.630 --> 00:05:10.630
and it shattered the glass on
the sixth floor bridge, which

00:05:10.630 --> 00:05:12.870
housed all the navigational
equipment and the power

00:05:12.870 --> 00:05:13.830
to our engines.

00:05:13.830 --> 00:05:15.720
And so we lost all
power to our engines

00:05:15.720 --> 00:05:17.810
while in 45 foot
swells surrounded

00:05:17.810 --> 00:05:20.400
by freezing cold
hypothermic water.

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:22.605
And I had a certain
death experiencing.

00:05:22.605 --> 00:05:25.595
I mean, the announcement
came telling

00:05:25.595 --> 00:05:27.220
us to get to the
fifth floor or higher,

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:28.970
help the women and
children up the stairs,

00:05:28.970 --> 00:05:31.327
keep on your life jackets,
and to your muster stations.

00:05:31.327 --> 00:05:32.785
And for those that
aren't familiar,

00:05:32.785 --> 00:05:35.120
a muster stations is where
you evacuate a ship from.

00:05:35.120 --> 00:05:37.260
So we were basically
told-- without saying it

00:05:37.260 --> 00:05:39.760
explicitly-- the ship's going
down and you have to evacuate.

00:05:39.760 --> 00:05:43.410
And I'm looking out at a small
mountain of freezing cold water

00:05:43.410 --> 00:05:45.810
with no ability to
get into lifeboats.

00:05:45.810 --> 00:05:48.960
And so I was sure I was
dying in the next hour,

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:50.210
there was no doubt in my mind.

00:05:50.210 --> 00:05:53.840
Went through the emotional
experience of that.

00:05:53.840 --> 00:05:56.515
