00:10:37.285 --> 00:10:40.780
of small donations from young
people especially through this

00:10:40.780 --> 00:10:43.990
social media thing you
keep on telling me about.

00:10:43.990 --> 00:10:47.160
And so he said, go with
five donors who can give you

00:10:47.160 --> 00:10:50.137
$50,000 each, and you have
$250,000 in startup capital,

00:10:50.137 --> 00:10:52.220
and then you can hire a
team and build from there.

00:10:52.220 --> 00:10:55.610
And if I was-- knowing
what I know now,

00:10:55.610 --> 00:10:57.110
I probably would
go in and say yeah,

00:10:57.110 --> 00:10:59.580
I should get a bunch of
high-net worth individuals

00:10:59.580 --> 00:11:01.205
and get a bunch of
capital and then you

00:11:01.205 --> 00:11:03.110
can springboard from
that point forward.

00:11:03.110 --> 00:11:06.070
But I was so committed to
proving that any person can

00:11:06.070 --> 00:11:08.780
create something of
large scale-- change--

00:11:08.780 --> 00:11:11.320
that I was willing to
go into a bank and say

00:11:11.320 --> 00:11:13.150
what does it take to
start a bank account.

00:11:13.150 --> 00:11:15.910
And they said $25 to open up
something at Bank of America.

00:11:15.910 --> 00:11:18.900
And so I put $25 in because one,
I didn't have a lot of money,

00:11:18.900 --> 00:11:21.860
and two, my friends certainly
had no money at the time,

00:11:21.860 --> 00:11:24.396
and I wanted to prove
that this could be done.

00:11:24.396 --> 00:11:24.895
And so--

00:11:24.895 --> 00:11:26.562
FEMALE SPEAKER: You
were 24 at the time?

00:11:26.562 --> 00:11:28.270
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah, it
was my 25th birthday

00:11:28.270 --> 00:11:29.920
at the launch of
the organization.

00:11:29.920 --> 00:11:31.176
And so--

00:11:31.176 --> 00:11:32.150
FEMALE SPEAKER: $25.

00:11:32.150 --> 00:11:32.500
ADAM BRAUN: Right.

00:11:32.500 --> 00:11:32.999
Right.

00:11:32.999 --> 00:11:35.887
And so if I was purely committed
to building the organization

00:11:35.887 --> 00:11:38.220
up, maybe I would have done
it a little bit differently.

00:11:38.220 --> 00:11:40.002
But the ambition has
never been to solely

00:11:40.002 --> 00:11:41.460
make Pencils of
Promise successful.

00:11:41.460 --> 00:11:45.795
It's to change the thinking that
people have around philanthropy

00:11:45.795 --> 00:11:47.780
and what we call a
nonprofit-- and I

00:11:47.780 --> 00:11:50.400
like to call for-purpose
organizations--

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:52.540
and hopefully inspire
people and then

00:11:52.540 --> 00:11:54.950
provide them with
the tools and ability

00:11:54.950 --> 00:11:57.250
to create their own
extraordinary journey that

00:11:57.250 --> 00:12:00.160
fulfills their sense of purpose.

00:12:00.160 --> 00:12:04.850
FEMALE SPEAKER: So with
that $25 that you started,

00:12:04.850 --> 00:12:08.800
besides that-- almost
more advice to people that

00:12:08.800 --> 00:12:11.750
are interested in starting
their own side-organization

00:12:11.750 --> 00:12:15.880
or organization-- what else are
the bare bones that you think

00:12:15.880 --> 00:12:19.420
that you need to
start an organization?

00:12:19.420 --> 00:12:23.730
You could forget the 5
giant $50,000 donation,

00:12:23.730 --> 00:12:28.480
but what are the bare bones
that you would advise?

00:12:28.480 --> 00:12:30.114
ADAM BRAUN: So there's
a lot, but if I

00:12:30.114 --> 00:12:34.080
was to distill it into,
let's say, three things.

00:12:34.080 --> 00:12:36.030
The first one is you
have to knowledge

00:12:36.030 --> 00:12:37.190
that it's going to work.

00:12:37.190 --> 00:12:38.763
And I'm not talking
about hope, and I'm not

00:12:38.763 --> 00:12:39.637
talking about belief.

00:12:39.637 --> 00:12:43.250
You have to be completely
delusional about the fact

00:12:43.250 --> 00:12:45.180
that your idea is
going to succeed,

00:12:45.180 --> 00:12:47.990
because you're going to
hear no, or that's nice

00:12:47.990 --> 00:12:51.340
but I'm not interested,
99.9% of the time.

00:12:51.340 --> 00:12:53.389
Even to this day, I
hear 99.9% of the time

00:12:53.389 --> 00:12:55.680
I explain to somebody what
we do and they make a choice

00:12:55.680 --> 00:12:57.380
not to support
Pencils of Promise.

00:12:57.380 --> 00:12:59.074
Just by their own volition, so--

00:12:59.074 --> 00:13:01.490
FEMALE SPEAKER: You'll hear
no way more than you hear yes.

00:13:01.490 --> 00:13:01.910
ADAM BRAUN: Right.

00:13:01.910 --> 00:13:02.410
Right.

00:13:02.410 --> 00:13:05.300
And so the first is you
can't think it's a good idea,

00:13:05.300 --> 00:13:07.690
you have to genuinely
believe that no matter what

00:13:07.690 --> 00:13:10.650
anybody else says this
thing has to succeed.

00:13:10.650 --> 00:13:13.720
And that, again, when it comes
from a place of purpose, which

00:13:13.720 --> 00:13:17.440
is beyond passion,
that's step number one.

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:19.786
The second one is--
there's a chapter called

00:13:19.786 --> 00:13:21.160
"Find The Impossible
Ones," which

00:13:21.160 --> 00:13:23.495
is you need to find your tribe.

00:13:23.495 --> 00:13:26.570
And I really advocate for people
almost creating an underdog

00:13:26.570 --> 00:13:30.057
sense around your organization
or your company or your idea.

00:13:30.057 --> 00:13:31.640
Because people rally
around underdogs.

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:33.514
There's a reason that
we watch March Madness.

00:13:33.514 --> 00:13:36.480
It's not in hopes that the
final bracket is 1, 1, 1, 1.

00:13:36.480 --> 00:13:39.860
It's that we want to see 8s
play against 15s and 15s win

00:13:39.860 --> 00:13:40.710
and somehow make it.

00:13:40.710 --> 00:13:42.210
Like that's the
stories that we love

00:13:42.210 --> 00:13:43.890
and the stories that we tell.

00:13:43.890 --> 00:13:46.537
And so as much as people
tell me this is impossible,

00:13:46.537 --> 00:13:47.786
I thought, well, that's great.

00:13:47.786 --> 00:13:49.260
I'm going to create a tribe.

00:13:49.260 --> 00:13:53.905
Like our team is going to be
people that embrace that idea.

00:13:53.905 --> 00:13:56.030
And so you have to have
like-minded individuals who

00:13:56.030 --> 00:13:57.280
become your early adopters.

00:13:57.280 --> 00:14:00.260
Because otherwise you're just
a lunatic preaching something

00:14:00.260 --> 00:14:02.370
that nobody believes in.

00:14:02.370 --> 00:14:04.032
And then the third
one is I genuinely

00:14:04.032 --> 00:14:05.740
believe that you have
to combine business

00:14:05.740 --> 00:14:09.510
acumen with the ideals found
your company, whether it's

00:14:09.510 --> 00:14:10.880
a nonprofit or for profit.

00:14:10.880 --> 00:14:14.730
But I've seen way too
many failed projects,

00:14:14.730 --> 00:14:16.900
nonprofit or for
profit, because people

00:14:16.900 --> 00:14:18.780
go into the space
with purely passion

00:14:18.780 --> 00:14:20.840
and they're not equipped
with business acumen.

00:14:20.840 --> 00:14:22.589
And I think that more
than anything that's

00:14:22.589 --> 00:14:25.010
what's enabled us to
succeed is the training

00:14:25.010 --> 00:14:27.830
that I had working at a hedge
fund when I was 16 or Bain

00:14:27.830 --> 00:14:29.480
out of college.

00:14:29.480 --> 00:14:31.280
It differentiated
me in the space.

00:14:31.280 --> 00:14:34.490
And the reason that we are
successful in our programs

00:14:34.490 --> 00:14:36.800
is because the business
acumen drives what we do.

00:14:36.800 --> 00:14:39.610
It's not just pretty pictures
and a flashy website.

00:14:39.610 --> 00:14:41.520
FEMALE SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:14:41.520 --> 00:14:45.710
So in the midst of all
of this growing in your--

00:14:45.710 --> 00:14:48.162
it's an amazing organization.

00:14:48.162 --> 00:14:50.350
Why did you decide
to write a book now?

00:14:50.350 --> 00:14:51.862
What was the motivation?

00:14:51.862 --> 00:14:53.320
ADAM BRAUN: There
was a few things.

00:14:53.320 --> 00:14:56.370
The first was that I had a
lot of people coming to me

00:14:56.370 --> 00:15:02.000
and asking the natural question
of saying, I have an idea.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.870
How did you turn $25 into
this big organization?

00:15:04.870 --> 00:15:06.720
Can you just sit with
me for 30 minutes?

00:15:06.720 --> 00:15:09.470
And after I did a bunch of
these phone calls and meetings,

00:15:09.470 --> 00:15:11.690
I found that I was often
inspired by the feedback

00:15:11.690 --> 00:15:12.960
that I was getting from them.

00:15:12.960 --> 00:15:16.020
But I didn't have the
time or the ability

00:15:16.020 --> 00:15:18.190
to give them all the
advice that I wanted.

00:15:18.190 --> 00:15:21.360
So the first thing was
literally to create

00:15:21.360 --> 00:15:23.740
a guidebook for any
other individual

00:15:23.740 --> 00:15:25.780
to pursue their thing,
whatever that might be--

00:15:25.780 --> 00:15:29.320
side job within a company,
something entrepreneurial.

00:15:29.320 --> 00:15:30.880
But I read a lot of
these great books

00:15:30.880 --> 00:15:32.910
and they were purely
inspiring narratives.

00:15:32.910 --> 00:15:35.469
And they didn't have
the how-to element.

00:15:35.469 --> 00:15:37.760
So that was the first thing
was I wanted to show people

00:15:37.760 --> 00:15:39.850
how they could go and do it.

00:15:39.850 --> 00:15:42.715
And then the second one was
that I wanted the organization

00:15:42.715 --> 00:15:45.130
to continue and
scale its impact.

00:15:45.130 --> 00:15:46.510
And either I could
get on a plane

00:15:46.510 --> 00:15:48.970
and try and speak on
every stage possible,

00:15:48.970 --> 00:15:51.277
or I could write something
that somebody else could

00:15:51.277 --> 00:15:52.860
hand to somebody
else and say, oh, you

00:15:52.860 --> 00:15:54.630
want to learn about
this organization?

00:15:54.630 --> 00:15:55.380
Read this book.

00:15:55.380 --> 00:15:57.740
And as part of that, all
proceeds from the book

00:15:57.740 --> 00:15:59.220
go back to the organization.

00:15:59.220 --> 00:16:00.428
FEMALE SPEAKER: That's great.

00:16:00.428 --> 00:16:03.180
ADAM BRAUN: And so it made it a
very easy decision for somebody

00:16:03.180 --> 00:16:04.885
to say to another
individual, hey,

00:16:04.885 --> 00:16:06.260
if you are interested
in learning

00:16:06.260 --> 00:16:08.330
about a great organization,
here's the PoP book.

00:16:08.330 --> 00:16:11.821
And this will provide with the
full background and the ability

00:16:11.821 --> 00:16:13.695
to either get involved
with this organization

00:16:13.695 --> 00:16:17.260
or to discover your own
passion and pursue it.

00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:19.830
FEMALE SPEAKER: From the
time that this idea came up

00:16:19.830 --> 00:16:21.370
to the time was
published, how long

00:16:21.370 --> 00:16:23.780
was this process of writing it?

00:16:23.780 --> 00:16:28.070
ADAM BRAUN: So one of
my bucket-list items

00:16:28.070 --> 00:16:30.090
was to write a book,
just because I think

00:16:30.090 --> 00:16:32.820
that it outlives the individual
and it was just a cool idea

00:16:32.820 --> 00:16:35.710
that 100 years from now
there'll be some digital library

00:16:35.710 --> 00:16:37.460
that Google has created
and this book will

00:16:37.460 --> 00:16:40.640
be in the digital library
that people can go and see

00:16:40.640 --> 00:16:42.960
with their robot eyes.

00:16:42.960 --> 00:16:46.710
So the idea has been
there for a long time,

00:16:46.710 --> 00:16:50.180
but the actual process
of writing was quick.

00:16:50.180 --> 00:16:52.600
I mapped it out
with my co-writer,

00:16:52.600 --> 00:16:55.580
Carly, over no more than
really three months.

00:16:55.580 --> 00:16:57.520
And then I took a
sabbatical last year

00:16:57.520 --> 00:17:00.060
with my fiance and
just a backpack each.

00:17:00.060 --> 00:17:02.200
We did around the world
trip for a little bit more

00:17:02.200 --> 00:17:03.220
than three months.

00:17:03.220 --> 00:17:05.849
And I brought a
computer in the backpack

00:17:05.849 --> 00:17:09.805
and so I would write most days
and send my draft back to Carly

00:17:09.805 --> 00:17:11.554
and she would give me
her little revisions

00:17:11.554 --> 00:17:14.260
and be like, pull out this
story, and more description

00:17:14.260 --> 00:17:17.210
here, and really
guide me through it.

00:17:17.210 --> 00:17:19.150
And so the entire
manuscript was actually

00:17:19.150 --> 00:17:20.700
written in three months,
which is really fast.

00:17:20.700 --> 00:17:22.079
FEMALE SPEAKER: That's
incredibly fast.

00:17:22.079 --> 00:17:22.787
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah.

00:17:22.787 --> 00:17:24.849
And the original mentions
was 81,000 words,

00:17:24.849 --> 00:17:26.619
and the final book is 66,000.

00:17:26.619 --> 00:17:29.390
So a fair amount was
actually cut out,

00:17:29.390 --> 00:17:31.610
but that was because I
wanted it to be an easy read.

00:17:31.610 --> 00:17:33.950
I wanted it to be something
that you could pick up

00:17:33.950 --> 00:17:36.309
in the airport on a
flight cross-country

00:17:36.309 --> 00:17:37.975
and read it by the
time that you landed.

00:17:37.975 --> 00:17:39.870
FEMALE SPEAKER: I think
I read it about two days.

00:17:39.870 --> 00:17:40.578
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah.

00:17:40.578 --> 00:17:43.370
I mean, that's been the most
consistent feedback thus far

00:17:43.370 --> 00:17:47.760
is I've read your book in no
more than three days for most

00:17:47.760 --> 00:17:48.260
people.

00:17:48.260 --> 00:17:50.399
It's like a weekend read
or flight read or their

00:17:50.399 --> 00:17:52.940
on the beach for the afternoon
and they just tear through it.

00:17:52.940 --> 00:17:55.930
FEMALE SPEAKER: Yeah,
it's a great read.

00:17:55.930 --> 00:17:57.790
Something that you
talked about earlier

00:17:57.790 --> 00:18:00.350
or brought up that I thought
was a really clever in the book

00:18:00.350 --> 00:18:02.370
is the way the chapters
are named after mantras.

00:18:05.170 --> 00:18:08.260
Why did you decide to
name them after mantras?

00:18:08.260 --> 00:18:10.520
ADAM BRAUN: So somebody
asked me at one point,

00:18:10.520 --> 00:18:13.250
there were 650 or 700 students
that went on your Semester

00:18:13.250 --> 00:18:13.965
at Sea voyage.

00:18:13.965 --> 00:18:16.140
What was it that was
different about you

00:18:16.140 --> 00:18:18.050
that you came back with
not only this feeling

00:18:18.050 --> 00:18:21.940
but then you converted
intention into action.

00:18:21.940 --> 00:18:25.020
And the truth is, if I
think about what led to it,

00:18:25.020 --> 00:18:28.390
I think it was the fact
that I just adopted mantras.

00:18:28.390 --> 00:18:31.290
And so I've always had
one powerful phrase

00:18:31.290 --> 00:18:32.590
that guides my decision-making.

00:18:32.590 --> 00:18:35.110
And it's tough to
have a set of values

00:18:35.110 --> 00:18:36.860
that you live by if
there's eight of them.

00:18:36.860 --> 00:18:41.010
But I think it's really simple
if you find one essential truth

00:18:41.010 --> 00:18:44.495
that you almost treat
as the guiding principle

00:18:44.495 --> 00:18:46.570
that you make all
your decisions around.

00:18:46.570 --> 00:18:50.390
And I find that oftentimes
I discover one phrase

00:18:50.390 --> 00:18:52.140
or I come up with
one phrase and that

00:18:52.140 --> 00:18:55.170
feels right for that
period of my life.

00:18:55.170 --> 00:18:58.230
And so given that I
found these phrases so

00:18:58.230 --> 00:19:00.950
helpful in my
decision-making process,

00:19:00.950 --> 00:19:03.260
I thought, the way we
consume media nowadays

00:19:03.260 --> 00:19:04.510
is really different.

00:19:04.510 --> 00:19:08.510
So we want 140 characters
that describe something,

00:19:08.510 --> 00:19:11.070
and then we want the ability
to click in an expand.

00:19:11.070 --> 00:19:13.790
And so when I read, most of
the time it's tough for me

00:19:13.790 --> 00:19:15.180
to read a whole book.

00:19:15.180 --> 00:19:18.137
I don't about you guys, but I'm
like eight-- there's probably

00:19:18.137 --> 00:19:20.010
eight books right now
that I'm between 50

00:19:20.010 --> 00:19:22.010
and 100 pages through.

00:19:22.010 --> 00:19:24.020
And I just kind of get
bored and I put it down.

00:19:24.020 --> 00:19:26.190
I'm like, all right, I
get the general principle.

00:19:26.190 --> 00:19:28.870
And so the one thing that I do
stick with is short stories.

00:19:28.870 --> 00:19:30.570
So I listen to Moth Podcasts.

00:19:30.570 --> 00:19:32.130
And I watch TED
Talks, and I like

00:19:32.130 --> 00:19:34.400
episodes of "House of Cards"
and "Game of Thrones,"

00:19:34.400 --> 00:19:36.434
and I like to watch
three if I want, or one.

00:19:36.434 --> 00:19:38.100
So I thought, why
can't you write a book

00:19:38.100 --> 00:19:41.070
with that same ideology,
the same kind of framework.

00:19:41.070 --> 00:19:45.460
So the mantras could be the
quick way to access something.

00:19:45.460 --> 00:19:46.880
And I'm sure you would agree.

00:19:46.880 --> 00:19:50.400
Someone could pick up this
book and read Mantra 13 alone,

00:19:50.400 --> 00:19:52.690
separate from the rest, and
feel like they gain value.

00:19:52.690 --> 00:19:54.070
FEMALE SPEAKER: Yeah,
that's very true.

00:19:54.070 --> 00:19:55.570
ADAM BRAUN: And so
I wanted to write

00:19:55.570 --> 00:19:58.485
in the way we consume
media nowadays as well,

00:19:58.485 --> 00:20:03.290
like episodic versions,
and ultimately the Mantras

00:20:03.290 --> 00:20:06.310
seemed like the best
way to frame it.

00:20:06.310 --> 00:20:08.540
FEMALE SPEAKER: It does
feel like episodes.

00:20:08.540 --> 00:20:11.229
Like each chapter does
really feel like an episode.

00:20:11.229 --> 00:20:13.520
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah, and I was
talking to a friend of mine

00:20:13.520 --> 00:20:16.260
yesterday who's written
a really fantastic book.

00:20:16.260 --> 00:20:19.280
And one of the things that
I was sharing with him

00:20:19.280 --> 00:20:23.770
is that when I wrote the book I
was traveling for three months.

00:20:23.770 --> 00:20:27.599
And I wanted to read great
books while I was traveling.

00:20:27.599 --> 00:20:29.890
And what I found is that
there is, and I won't name it,

00:20:29.890 --> 00:20:31.395
there's one book that was
an international bestseller

00:20:31.395 --> 00:20:33.470
on a topic that I'm
so interested in,

00:20:33.470 --> 00:20:35.680
but as I read it
was really dense.

00:20:35.680 --> 00:20:37.290
It was like a textbook.

00:20:37.290 --> 00:20:40.030
And it wasn't enjoyable
for me to read.

00:20:40.030 --> 00:20:41.990
But when I thought about
the books that I did

00:20:41.990 --> 00:20:44.240
enjoy they were kind
of these page turners

00:20:44.240 --> 00:20:47.340
that left little hooks
at the end of a chapter

00:20:47.340 --> 00:20:50.409
when I'd want to kind of put
it down and go get lunch.

00:20:50.409 --> 00:20:51.950
I'd almost be like,
but, wait, I need

00:20:51.950 --> 00:20:54.580
to know what happens next,
because he or she previewed

00:20:54.580 --> 00:20:56.170
what's about to happen.

00:20:56.170 --> 00:20:57.930
And so selectively--
it probably happens

00:20:57.930 --> 00:21:00.100
six or seven times
throughout the book--

00:21:00.100 --> 00:21:02.740
but at the end of a chapter
I would just kind of

00:21:02.740 --> 00:21:05.160
plug in what's
coming next, and then

00:21:05.160 --> 00:21:08.940
paint that scene in the next
paragraph on the side page.

00:21:08.940 --> 00:21:11.310
And I found that it's
really enabled people

00:21:11.310 --> 00:21:13.990
