00:35:55.870 --> 00:35:56.370
recorder.

00:35:56.370 --> 00:35:58.140
And I couldn't really
understand why.

00:35:58.140 --> 00:36:00.700
And then I came to realize he
had a big set of headphones,

00:36:00.700 --> 00:36:02.260
and he was teaching
himself English.

00:36:02.260 --> 00:36:03.757
And he was teacher.

00:36:03.757 --> 00:36:05.590
And he couldn't pronounce
English very well.

00:36:05.590 --> 00:36:09.550
So the goal was for him
to listen to my voice

00:36:09.550 --> 00:36:11.590
pronouncing the words
properly so he could teach

00:36:11.590 --> 00:36:13.160
himself to then teach his kids.

00:36:13.160 --> 00:36:15.526
Completely changed my philosophy
on global development,

00:36:15.526 --> 00:36:17.150
because he wasn't
asking for a handout.

00:36:17.150 --> 00:36:19.250
He wanted the tools
to self-educate,

00:36:19.250 --> 00:36:21.590
and then pass it down
to future generations.

00:36:21.590 --> 00:36:24.680
And so that's informed every
one of the philosophies that's

00:36:24.680 --> 00:36:25.940
launched the organization.

00:36:25.940 --> 00:36:30.890
So, for example, we don't build
schools on behalf of villages.

00:36:30.890 --> 00:36:32.810
Villages have to
commit to 10 to 20,

00:36:32.810 --> 00:36:34.740
and now it's almost
always 20%, or more

00:36:34.740 --> 00:36:37.290
of the funding for every
project that we undertake.

00:36:37.290 --> 00:36:39.660
They have no spare cash,
because it's $300 to $500

00:36:39.660 --> 00:36:42.810
in annual income for the
family in most communities

00:36:42.810 --> 00:36:43.620
where we work.

00:36:43.620 --> 00:36:45.370
So they make it up in
materials and labor.

00:36:45.370 --> 00:36:47.619
So they collect the scrapwood,
the gravel, the cement.

00:36:47.619 --> 00:36:49.637
And then more importantly
mothers and fathers

00:36:49.637 --> 00:36:51.220
and elders and
siblings are physically

00:36:51.220 --> 00:36:52.404
building the schools.

00:36:52.404 --> 00:36:53.820
They provide almost
all the labor.

00:36:53.820 --> 00:36:57.140
In Ghana it's 100% of labor
is provided by the community.

00:36:57.140 --> 00:37:00.120
And that creates a sense of
real ownership and investment,

00:37:00.120 --> 00:37:02.264
because we don't do
build trips, for example.

00:37:02.264 --> 00:37:04.680
Like if somebody asks me, can
I go out and build a school,

00:37:04.680 --> 00:37:05.580
and live in a village
for three weeks,

00:37:05.580 --> 00:37:08.152
my answer is no, because I
want these communities to build

00:37:08.152 --> 00:37:10.360
their own school so that
when it starts to break down

00:37:10.360 --> 00:37:13.303
they don't say, hey, where was
that college kid from Wisconsin

00:37:13.303 --> 00:37:15.386
that built my school,
because the piping's broken.

00:37:15.386 --> 00:37:15.940
It's no, no.

00:37:15.940 --> 00:37:17.524
I built my son's school.

00:37:17.524 --> 00:37:18.690
It's starting to break down.

00:37:18.690 --> 00:37:19.405
I need to fix it.

00:37:19.405 --> 00:37:20.780
And he needs to
make sure he gets

00:37:20.780 --> 00:37:22.460
his butt in the
classroom every day.

00:37:22.460 --> 00:37:25.440
And so there's a
whole set of practices

00:37:25.440 --> 00:37:28.310
in place across the organization
that insure local ownership

00:37:28.310 --> 00:37:29.101
and sustainability.

