building 1,000 schools,

00:42:39.535 --> 00:42:43.570
but if that doesn't lead to
the mission being solved,

00:42:43.570 --> 00:42:45.190
then we're not doing
the right thing.

00:42:45.190 --> 00:42:48.270
And so my hope is that
five years from now

00:42:48.270 --> 00:42:51.395
we're doing something that
I don't even know about.

00:42:51.395 --> 00:42:53.018
Five years ago,
there's no chance

00:42:53.018 --> 00:42:55.184
I would have told you about
e-readers in classrooms,

00:42:55.184 --> 00:42:57.390
because it just
wasn't even an idea.

00:42:57.390 --> 00:43:01.170
And so my hope is we're almost
like, if you watch a baby

00:43:01.170 --> 00:43:03.660
walking, you know, like
they're almost falling forward,

00:43:03.660 --> 00:43:05.950
but they always somehow
catch themselves.

00:43:05.950 --> 00:43:08.170
And the idea is to
move the organization

00:43:08.170 --> 00:43:09.992
with that type of momentum.

00:43:14.176 --> 00:43:15.426
FEMALE SPEAKER: Any questions?

00:43:20.235 --> 00:43:20.860
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:43:20.860 --> 00:43:22.943
I was wondering if you
could say a little bit more

00:43:22.943 --> 00:43:25.306
about your data-driven approach
to solving [INAUDIBLE].

00:43:25.306 --> 00:43:28.932
It seems to be a common
theme now in a lot of NGOs.

00:43:28.932 --> 00:43:29.890
ADAM BRAUN: Completely.

00:43:29.890 --> 00:43:33.350
So I think the Gates
Foundation has probably

00:43:33.350 --> 00:43:35.760
moved the space in that
direction more than any other,

00:43:35.760 --> 00:43:39.010
because they've just applied
so much rigorous data driven

00:43:39.010 --> 00:43:42.654
monitoring and evaluation to
the way that they issue grants,

00:43:42.654 --> 00:43:43.570
as well as Robin Hood.

00:43:43.570 --> 00:43:45.670
Robin Hood's about as
data-driven as it gets.

00:43:45.670 --> 00:43:48.589
So one of the things that's
really important to us

00:43:48.589 --> 00:43:51.130
is that we're not purely driven
by passion, but by commitment

00:43:51.130 --> 00:43:51.750
to results.

00:43:51.750 --> 00:43:54.420
And so we track about
25 different metrics

00:43:54.420 --> 00:43:56.370
in every community after
a school is opened.

00:43:56.370 --> 00:43:59.060
So that's everything
from teacher attention,

00:43:59.060 --> 00:44:01.750
to student attendance,
to literacy progression,

00:44:01.750 --> 00:44:04.450
grade progression, numeracy.

00:44:04.450 --> 00:44:08.070
And what we're seeing is
some really compelling data.

00:44:08.070 --> 00:44:10.391
So kids that go
through classrooms

00:44:10.391 --> 00:44:12.140
where we've provided
our teaching training

00:44:12.140 --> 00:44:15.630
outperform peer communities
three to one on test scores.

00:44:15.630 --> 00:44:17.315
85% of the communities
where we work

00:44:17.315 --> 00:44:19.650
are reporting
increases in literacy.

00:44:19.650 --> 00:44:22.550
And kids in Pencils
of Promise schools

00:44:22.550 --> 00:44:25.590
are progressing from one
grade to the next at two times

00:44:25.590 --> 00:44:27.010
the national average.

00:44:27.010 --> 00:44:30.580
And so that to me is what's,
truthfully, most important.

00:44:30.580 --> 00:44:34.910
So this is a little bit jargony,
but the nonprofit space always

00:44:34.910 --> 00:44:37.460
celebrates outputs.

00:44:37.460 --> 00:44:40.200
And so the output would be
broke ground on 200 schools,

00:44:40.200 --> 00:44:44.660
22,000-plus kids
in our classrooms,

00:44:44.660 --> 00:44:47.340
and 15 million education
hours delivered.

00:44:47.340 --> 00:44:48.810
And those are
nice, flashy stats,

00:44:48.810 --> 00:44:50.820
and people say, wow,
that's really great.

00:44:50.820 --> 00:44:54.360
But the analogy of that
would be for a company

00:44:54.360 --> 00:44:58.410
to purely be based on the
amount of employees they have.

00:44:58.410 --> 00:45:00.329
Or, you know, I define
it to background.

00:45:00.329 --> 00:45:02.120
So it'd be like someone
saying, hey, I just

00:45:02.120 --> 00:45:04.780
launched an investment fund,
and we have $25 million

00:45:04.780 --> 00:45:06.175
under management.

00:45:06.175 --> 00:45:08.490
Now, that's great,
but all that matters

00:45:08.490 --> 00:45:11.170
is what's the performance
of your investment strategy.

00:45:11.170 --> 00:45:14.690
So if you have $25 million under
management but you're down 30%

00:45:14.690 --> 00:45:17.000
on the year, you're
not doing a good job.

00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:18.800
And yet the nonprofit
space kind of

00:45:18.800 --> 00:45:23.380
has this free pass, where
people assume, oh, I gave $100,

00:45:23.380 --> 00:45:24.790
I got my $100 tax deduction.

00:45:24.790 --> 00:45:26.310
I did good in the world.

00:45:26.310 --> 00:45:30.430
And oftentimes that $100 is
either used ineffectively--

00:45:30.430 --> 00:45:32.724
sometimes it has
unintended consequence

00:45:32.724 --> 00:45:35.630
that are adversely
effecting the communities.

00:45:35.630 --> 00:45:39.790
And so our commitment
is to always stay

00:45:39.790 --> 00:45:41.910
held accountable to
the results themselves.

00:45:41.910 --> 00:45:44.170
And so we kill programs often.

00:45:44.170 --> 00:45:46.134
We mapped out all
of our programs,

00:45:46.134 --> 00:45:48.550
and we were doing something,
it was called Sister Schools.

00:45:48.550 --> 00:45:51.020
So we pairing together schools
in low income communities,

00:45:51.020 --> 00:45:54.370
in the Bronx, and Queens,
and parts of the city,

00:45:54.370 --> 00:45:56.370
and parts of California
with some of our schools

00:45:56.370 --> 00:45:57.430
internationally.

00:45:57.430 --> 00:45:59.014
And, you know, parents
and individuals

00:45:59.014 --> 00:46:00.263
were like, can we do pen pals?

00:46:00.263 --> 00:46:00.779
We did it.

00:46:00.779 --> 00:46:02.070
We thought it was a great idea.

00:46:02.070 --> 00:46:04.330
And then when we mapped
it out on a two by two,

00:46:04.330 --> 00:46:06.087
and kind of did
consulting style work,

00:46:06.087 --> 00:46:07.920
we realized, all right,
this is actually not

00:46:07.920 --> 00:46:10.267
advancing our mission
very effectively.

00:46:10.267 --> 00:46:12.100
It's not advancing the
fundraising component

00:46:12.100 --> 00:46:12.960
of the organization.

00:46:12.960 --> 00:46:17.410
And it's a huge effort on behalf
of our time, energy, resources,

00:46:17.410 --> 00:46:18.020
our staff.

00:46:18.020 --> 00:46:20.600
And so we stopped the program
because it was ineffective.

00:46:20.600 --> 00:46:22.330
Now, it would be
nice for me to show

00:46:22.330 --> 00:46:24.360
you pictures of kids in
the Bronx communicating

00:46:24.360 --> 00:46:26.360
with kids in rural Laos,
and everyone would say,

00:46:26.360 --> 00:46:27.175
oh, I feel so good.

00:46:27.175 --> 00:46:30.090
But it was an ineffective
usage of our dollar.

00:46:30.090 --> 00:46:32.020
And so when you have
a data-driven approach

00:46:32.020 --> 00:46:34.980
I think you make those
emotionally tough decisions.

00:46:34.980 --> 00:46:37.105
But if you're committed to
the mission achievement,

00:46:37.105 --> 00:46:39.246
then it's a no-brainer.

00:46:47.542 --> 00:46:49.982
AUDIENCE: So I wanted
to sort of understand

00:46:49.982 --> 00:46:52.422
a question that you asked.

00:46:52.422 --> 00:46:54.154
[INAUDIBLE]

00:46:54.154 --> 00:46:54.862
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah.

00:46:54.862 --> 00:46:57.310
AUDIENCE: But I wanted
to like focus it around

00:46:57.310 --> 00:47:01.680
how we could apply technology
advances to this mission.

00:47:01.680 --> 00:47:03.600
And I want to ask the
question this way.

00:47:03.600 --> 00:47:06.480
Just sort of think about
some big things that we do,

00:47:06.480 --> 00:47:07.440
and [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:10.660 --> 00:47:14.480
If you could have a bunch of
[INAUDIBLE] for six months,

00:47:14.480 --> 00:47:17.360
what would you have them do?

00:47:17.360 --> 00:47:20.040
ADAM BRAUN: Great question.

00:47:20.040 --> 00:47:24.886
So the underlying,
I guess, variable

00:47:24.886 --> 00:47:27.010
is whether there's Wi-Fi
access in our communities,

00:47:27.010 --> 00:47:28.900
which there is currently not.

00:47:28.900 --> 00:47:30.920
And so the first
thing I would say

00:47:30.920 --> 00:47:32.765
is bringing Wi-Fi access
to every community

00:47:32.765 --> 00:47:33.670
in which we worked.

00:47:33.670 --> 00:47:35.350
If I could get that
in itself, like

00:47:35.350 --> 00:47:36.967
that would be the Moonshot.

00:47:36.967 --> 00:47:38.550
I think that, whatever,
it's something

00:47:38.550 --> 00:47:41.990
like 4 billion people are
not currently connected.

00:47:41.990 --> 00:47:44.830
And so if we could connect every
single one of our communities

00:47:44.830 --> 00:47:47.620
into the internet
in some capacity,

00:47:47.620 --> 00:47:49.520
that would be the dream.

00:47:49.520 --> 00:47:52.060
But because it's probably,
let's say, five years away--

00:47:52.060 --> 00:47:54.770
it's not that far away--
but in the meantime

00:47:54.770 --> 00:47:57.280
I think there's some really
interesting capabilities

00:47:57.280 --> 00:48:00.450
around mobile access
in communities,

00:48:00.450 --> 00:48:03.010
and provision of
content, quality content.

00:48:03.010 --> 00:48:05.130
Because what we
see is most people

00:48:05.130 --> 00:48:07.810
have mobile phones,
certainly in Ghana.

00:48:07.810 --> 00:48:10.630
They're starting to get them in
Guatemala at pretty high rates.

00:48:10.630 --> 00:48:13.260
Laos is less frequent, but
somebody in the community

00:48:13.260 --> 00:48:14.590
has a mobile phone.

00:48:14.590 --> 00:48:18.950
And there should be some
type of content delivery

00:48:18.950 --> 00:48:20.390
system within feature phones.

00:48:20.390 --> 00:48:22.790
So right now people are mainly
focused on smart phones,

00:48:22.790 --> 00:48:24.920
but the communities where
we work don't have those.

00:48:24.920 --> 00:48:27.830
So I would almost ask
engineers to say, OK,

00:48:27.830 --> 00:48:29.466
what is the mobile
capacity going

00:48:29.466 --> 00:48:32.210
to be in this community
in the next three years?

00:48:32.210 --> 00:48:34.360
And then how do we build
a content delivery system

00:48:34.360 --> 00:48:35.610
so that they can self educate?

00:48:38.995 --> 00:48:40.975
FEMALE SPEAKER: Time
for one more question.

00:48:47.420 --> 00:48:52.848
AUDIENCE: So you have these
organizations like [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:52.848 --> 00:49:04.256
What's your take on, since
you're [INAUDIBLE] organization

00:49:04.256 --> 00:49:06.736
maybe it's going to
be really good at it

00:49:06.736 --> 00:49:08.720
at the end of the year.

00:49:08.720 --> 00:49:11.402
What's your thinking
on [INAUDIBLE]?

00:49:11.402 --> 00:49:12.110
ADAM BRAUN: Sure.

00:49:12.110 --> 00:49:14.730
So, one, I would
never personally knock

00:49:14.730 --> 00:49:17.610
anyone that's trying to create a
positive influence in the world

00:49:17.610 --> 00:49:19.050
and in the lives of others.

00:49:19.050 --> 00:49:21.450
So it's hard for me to say
this is a bad organization

00:49:21.450 --> 00:49:23.860
unless they actually
do bad things.

00:49:23.860 --> 00:49:26.340
My personal preference,
my genuine belief,

00:49:26.340 --> 00:49:28.300
is that the single
most powerful way

00:49:28.300 --> 00:49:30.817
to bring positive
aid to the world

00:49:30.817 --> 00:49:32.805
is through greater
access of opportunity,

00:49:32.805 --> 00:49:35.290
to not dictate what somebody
should or shouldn't do,

00:49:35.290 --> 00:49:37.775
but purely to give them
the opportunity to choose.

00:49:37.775 --> 00:49:40.260
And there's no more
powerful way to do that

00:49:40.260 --> 00:49:41.751
than through education.

00:49:41.751 --> 00:49:44.236
The second thing is from
a data-driven approach.

00:49:44.236 --> 00:49:46.721
The only measured
way that has proven

00:49:46.721 --> 00:49:48.709
effective to raise
a country's GDP

00:49:48.709 --> 00:49:51.691
is through greater access
to education and attainment

00:49:51.691 --> 00:49:55.162
through educational achievement
of primary age children.

00:49:55.162 --> 00:49:56.661
It's just the only
thing that's been

00:49:56.661 --> 00:49:58.649
proven to lift up
GDP's consistently.

00:49:58.649 --> 00:50:00.637
And so when I look
at that, and I think,

00:50:00.637 --> 00:50:02.920
OK, education, now I
have the data behind it.

00:50:02.920 --> 00:50:05.170
I have the personal
preference towards it.

00:50:05.170 --> 00:50:08.290
And in my opinion it's
the only root cause

00:50:08.290 --> 00:50:09.350
that lifts up all others.

00:50:09.350 --> 00:50:11.100
So when you look at
discrimination issues,

00:50:11.100 --> 00:50:13.570
when you look at
disease, education

00:50:13.570 --> 00:50:16.287
is the one that just
has some type of kind

00:50:16.287 --> 00:50:18.510
of residual impact on the rest.

00:50:18.510 --> 00:50:20.980
And my second thing
is around health.

00:50:20.980 --> 00:50:24.060
Health and education
are tied hand in hand.

00:50:24.060 --> 00:50:28.169
But my personal passion has
always been around education.

00:50:28.169 --> 00:50:32.033
But if somebody
works on-- I mean,

00:50:32.033 --> 00:50:34.931
there's an MIT study
that tried to say,

00:50:34.931 --> 00:50:37.730
what is the most dollar for
dollar effective intervention,

00:50:37.730 --> 00:50:39.372
[INAUDIBLE].

00:50:39.372 --> 00:50:41.610
Now, that said,
that's like in a lab.

00:50:41.610 --> 00:50:42.318
It's theoretical.

00:50:42.318 --> 00:50:45.755
It's think-tanks
putting it together.

00:50:45.755 --> 00:50:48.210
But for me it's
always been access

00:50:48.210 --> 00:50:51.156
to quality education, and
in particular, for youth.

00:50:51.156 --> 00:50:53.485
And so I wouldn't knock
any other organization,

00:50:53.485 --> 00:50:56.810
but I think there's something
powerful within that.

00:50:56.810 --> 00:51:03.160
And the last part for me is
that the former CEO of Malaria

00:51:03.160 --> 00:51:04.830
No More said this
to me outright.

00:51:04.830 --> 00:51:07.420
He said education is the
most stupidly solvable issue

00:51:07.420 --> 00:51:09.702
of our time, because
we have everything

00:51:09.702 --> 00:51:11.166
needed to educate every child.

00:51:11.166 --> 00:51:13.118
So with malaria
there's vaccinations.

00:51:13.118 --> 00:51:15.110
There are bed nets that
may or may not work.

00:51:15.110 --> 00:51:17.744
With water you have to dig for
aquifers that you're not sure

00:51:17.744 --> 00:51:18.910
if they're going to show up.

00:51:18.910 --> 00:51:21.694
With prevention
of AIDS or cancer,

00:51:21.694 --> 00:51:23.110
again, you'll have
to do research.

00:51:23.110 --> 00:51:26.246
And diabetes, we just don't
have the solution known yet.

00:51:26.246 --> 00:51:28.576
With education we have
everything, right now,

00:51:28.576 --> 00:51:30.290
to educate every child on Earth.

00:51:30.290 --> 00:51:33.332
And within that knowledge
gives me confidence

00:51:33.332 --> 00:51:36.410
that it's the thing that I like
to work on, because I believe

00:51:36.410 --> 00:51:38.192
I can solve it-- not
I, but collectively

00:51:38.192 --> 00:51:41.108
we together-- can
actually solve this,

00:51:41.108 --> 00:51:44.024
which gives me a
lot of excitement.

